					<physDesc rend="visible">
						<p>Vellum codex of the 15th century.</p>
						<objectDesc form="codex">
							<supportDesc material="perg">
								<support>Parchment codex. </support>
								<extent>145 folios <dimensions unit="mm" type="leaf">
										<height>343</height>
										<width>152</width>
									</dimensions>
								</extent>
								<foliation>
									<p>145 folios (+ 1 unfoliated paper flyleaf at the beginning and 2 unfoliated paper folios at the end of the manuscript). </p>
								</foliation>
								<collation>
									<p>14 quires: i12 (folios 1-12), ii10 (folios 13-22), iii6 (folios 23-28), iv-xiii10 (folios 29-137), xiv8 (folios 138-145).  </p>
								</collation>
							</supportDesc>
							<layoutDesc>
								<layout columns="2" ruledLines="25" writtenLines="25">
									<p>Four blank lines are found between any two books. </p>
									<p>The beginning of each pericope is marked in the margin by a large ornamental letter samekh. </p>
									<p>Each pericope is divided into 7 subsections, numbered in Hebrew letters in the margin. </p>
									<p>The masorah magna occupies 3 to 5 lines in the upper and 3 to 6 lines in the lower margin. </p>
									<p>Numerous masoretic rubrics at the end of each book of the Torah, as well as at the end of the whole Pentateuch. </p>
								</layout>
							</layoutDesc>
						</objectDesc>
						<handDesc hands="1">
							<summary>Yemenite square script, punctuate, of the 15th century. <name type="person" role="scribe">David ben Benayah ben Sa'adyah ben Zekhariah</name>, inscribed with his name in the colophon on folio 144r.</summary>
							<handNote script="Hebrew" scope="major"/>
